ogical, morphosyntactic, lexical and discourse features which are characteristic of the dialect.A discussion of the historical development of New Zealand English.A description of the current social and regional variation within the variety.An indication of the areas where change is currently occurring. Sample texts and an annotated bibliography of relevant literature.There are also several associated audio files, which provide examples of many of the phenomena discussed: http://www.lel.ed.ac.uk/dialects/"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEnglish languagexVariationzNew Zealand. 0aEnglish languagezNew Zealand. 4aLanguage & Linguistics. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Grammar & Punctuation.2bisacsh1 aGordon, Elizabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMaclagan, Margaret A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074862529140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780748630882?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748630882423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748630882/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK